</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3D7697363576FFE1FEF7F96C66A4F8DA" blockId="26.[264,1325,284,1798]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Remarks. 
<taxonomicName id="FAC9ECB53576FFE1FE61F96C658FF969" authorityName="Scarbrough Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[430,678,1692,1717]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamulus">
<emphasis id="0FBD4B243576FFE1FE61F96C658FF969" box="[430,678,1692,1717]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Afroestricus hamulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from congeners by the characters in the key and terminalia (
<figureCitation id="A5F28BB33576FFE1FE55F934651AF902" box="[410,563,1732,1758]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–54" captionStartId="25.[264,370,1625,1646]" captionTargetBox="[300,1295,402,1610]" captionTargetId="figure-130@25.[291,1315,390,1623]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 45–54. Afroestricus hamulus, sp. n. Male terminalia: 45–47. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views. 48. Gonostylus. 49–50. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Female terminalia: 51–52. Dorsal and ventral views. 53. Spermatheca. 54. Genital fork." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5050629" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5050629/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Figs. 45–54</figureCitation>
), especially the prominently hooked apical margin of the epandrium.
</paragraph>
